5|$|Christian baptismal {{theology}} {{prior to}} the Reformation taught that sacraments, including baptism, are means or instruments through which God communicates grace to people. The sacrament was considered valid regardless of who administered it. Not everyone who received a sacrament, however, received the grace signified by the sacrament. Some medieval theologians spoke of an obstacle of mortal sin which blocks the grace of the sacrament, while others insisted that the recipient be positively open and responding in faith to the sacrament {{in order to receive}} any benefit. Baptism was believed to be used by the <b>Holy</b> <b>Spirit</b> to transform the believer, and offered the benefits of remission of sins, regeneration, and the indwelling of the <b>Holy</b> <b>Spirit.</b> The sacrament of penance was believed to be necessary for forgiveness for sins committed after baptism.|$|E
